    "content": "Updates and corrections\n- ND root-invariance: We rely exclusively on the cylinder refinement criterion, which is root-free for saturated sets S_P. No use of Int(cl(S)) being saturated is needed.\n- Quotient caveat: The saturation of a cylinder need not be open (e.g., the cylinder “root has degree 1” saturates to “has a leaf somewhere,” an F_sigma but not open set). Thus forget-the-root quotient arguments that require π(C) to be open are invalid in this topology.\n- Theorem 4 status: As stated (no 1-way infinite bridges ⇒ weak 6-flow) it is false; the infinite D-regular tree (D≥3) has no nonzero weak flow. A correct direction requires assuming bridgelessness.\n- Bridges: Even D-regular graphs admit 2-way infinite bridges (regular tree example) but forbid 1-way bridges by parity; odd D admits 1-way bridges.\n\nMeagre result for 2-way bridges (D≥3)\n- For each k, let Br_≤k be rootings with a bridge within distance ≤k of the root. Given any nonempty cylinder B_r(G,ρ), pick R≫r+k and build a layered refinement so that from each edge e within distance ≤k one can route internally to two distinct boundary vertices; then, beyond the outer sphere, add a finite merger network joining those boundary pairs. In every completion, each such e lies on a cycle. Hence Br_≤k is nowhere dense. The union over k is meagre.\n- Density: Inside any cylinder, we can complete to an infinite graph and far outside attach an infinite component by a single edge to the existing infinite part. This produces a 2-way infinite bridge. Thus the property is meagre but not nowhere dense. Root-invariance follows since the set is saturated.\n\nΔ=D completion (sketch): If all vertices at distance <R have degree D in the refined ball and at least one boundary vertex has spare degree, then there exists a D-regular infinite extension preserving the R-ball (see proofs). This supports the Δ=D case of the merger construction.\n\nOpen directions\n- General meagre root-invariance remains open. Continue with partial homeomorphisms (marker-based re-rooting) on a comeagre domain, or isolate broader classes P where k-local avoidance suffices."
