  "proofs_update": {
    "action": "append",
    "content": "Lemma A (Δ=D ball completion). Let D≥3 and let F be a finite rooted graph of radius R with root ρ. Assume (i) every vertex v with dist_F(ρ,v)<R has deg_F(v)=D; and (ii) at least one vertex x in the outer layer L_R has deg_F(x)<D. Then there exists a countably infinite connected D-regular graph G with B_R(G,ρ)≅F.\nProof. For each x∈L_R, let q(x)=D−deg_F(x)≥0 and s=∑_{x∈L_R}q(x)≥1. Build an external reservoir as follows. Take a single infinite D-regular tree T, and delete a countable family M={e_i=u_i v_i : i∈ℕ} of pairwise edge-disjoint edges. In the resulting graph T−M, the set U={u_i,v_i : i∈ℕ} consists of vertices of degree D−1; all other vertices retain degree D. Choose distinct w_1,…,w_s∈U, and partition {w_1,…,w_s} into subsets of sizes {q(x)} indexed by x∈L_R. Form G_0 by taking the disjoint union of F and T−M and, for each x∈L_R, adding edges from x to its assigned q(x) vertices in U. Now every x∈L_R attains degree D; each chosen w_j∈U attains degree D. The remaining vertices in U (still countably many) have degree D−1. Enumerate the connected components of T−M and select one remaining degree-(D−1) vertex from each component; pair these selected vertices along a bi-infinite chain by adding edges between consecutive ones, and pair all other remaining degree-(D−1) vertices arbitrarily in disjoint edges. This yields a graph O in which all vertices have degree D and O is connected. Let G be the union of F and O with the attachment edges added above. Then G is connected and D-regular. Since all new neighbors of vertices at distance <R lie outside L_R, B_R(G,ρ)=F. ∎\n\nProposition B (k-local bridges are nowhere dense for D≥3). Fix D≥3 and k∈ℕ. Let Br_≤k be the set of rooted graphs (G,ρ) in G_{•,≤D} or G_{•,=D} that have a bridge at distance ≤k from ρ. Then Br_≤k is nowhere dense.\nProof. Let C(F_0) be a nonempty cylinder of radius r. Choose R≫r+k. Extend F_0 to a layered finite ball F_1 of radius R by adding new layers r+1,…,R so that: (a) all vertices at distance <R have degree ≤D and, in the Δ=D case, exactly D; (b) every vertex in the outer layer L_R has degree 1 (only the back-edge to L_{R−1}). Let E_k be the finite set of edges e of F_1 whose endpoints lie at distance ≤k from ρ.\nFor each e=ab∈E_k, choose two internally vertex-disjoint a→L_R and b→L_R paths in F_1 that avoid e (possible since between r and R we can allocate disjoint forward branches; choose R large enough to separate these finitely many requirements). Let their endpoints in L_R be denoted b_e^+ and b_e^−, with all these endpoints distinct across different e. Outside L_R, build a finite merger tree S whose leaves are in bijection with the set B={b_e^+,b_e^−: e∈E_k}, and join each such leaf to its corresponding boundary vertex in L_R. Let F′ be the resulting finite ball of radius R′>R (add only edges and vertices beyond L_R). In the Δ= D case, all vertices at distance <R already have degree D; in the Δ≤D case, all degrees remain ≤D; S can be chosen with maximum degree 3≤D. By construction, for any completion H of F′ (Δ≤D or, using Lemma A, Δ=D) and any e∈E_k, there is an H-path from b_e^+ to b_e^− that avoids e, so e lies on a cycle. Thus no edge within distance ≤k of ρ is a bridge in any completion of F′, i.e., C(F′)⊆C(F_0)\\Br_≤k. Therefore Br_≤k is nowhere dense. ∎\n\nCorollary C (2-way infinite bridges are meagre but not nowhere dense for D≥3). Let S_{2w} be the set of rootings whose underlying graph has a 2-way infinite bridge. Then S_{2w} is meagre and dense in G_{•,≤D} and in G_{•,=D} for D≥3.\nProof. Write S_{2w}=⋃_{k≥0} Br_≤k; by Proposition B each Br_≤k is nowhere dense, hence S_{2w} is meagre. For density, given any cylinder C(F_0), extend beyond a large radius to obtain an infinite completion A; attach an additional infinite tree T disjoint from A and join A to T by a single edge e whose endpoints lie outside the prescribed ball. Then e is a 2-way infinite bridge in the resulting completion, which lies in C(F_0). This works under Δ≤D; for Δ=D, first ensure (by extending the ball) two designated boundary vertices have spare degree and attach the two infinite D-regular trees at those vertices before adding e; Lemma A provides D-regular completions. Hence S_{2w} is dense. ∎"
  },
